{
  "query": "What are the observed outcomes of transplanting or seeding organisms onto intertidal artificial structures in Australian estuaries?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across studies that included estuaries in southeast Australia, transplanting oysters onto intertidal artificial structures supported macroalgae, mobile and non\u2011mobile invertebrates, and fish species that were absent from untreated structure surfaces [3472]. Effects on combined macroalgae and invertebrate richness/diversity were mixed and depended on site and the presence/size of grooves, small ridges, or ledges on surfaces [3472]. One study in Australia reported increased mobile invertebrate species richness on treated surfaces [3472]. For fishes, two of three Australian studies found no increase in species richness, while one found mixed effects depending on surface features and site [3472]. For abundance, one Australian study found no increase in combined macroalgae and invertebrates, and another found mixed effects depending on surface micro\u2011features [3472]. Invertebrate abundance responses were mixed; findings included increased non\u2011mobile invertebrate and oyster recruit abundance and decreased barnacle abundance in one study, and increased oyster and mobile invertebrate abundance in another [3472]. Fish abundance generally did not increase in two of three Australian studies, and in one study was similar regardless of groove/ridge size [3472]. Survival of transplanted invertebrates (including oysters) varied with species, site, and microhabitat features; oyster survival was higher in grooves than on ridges in one study, and survival in grooves/ledges varied by site in another [3472]. A behavioral study in Australia found no increase in time fishes interacted with surfaces or number of bites after transplanting oysters and/or coralline algae, though benthic fishes took more bites from surfaces with transplanted oysters than from those with algae plus oysters; these results held regardless of grooves/ridges [3472].",
  "action_ids": [
    "3472"
  ]
}

