{
  "query": "How do the effects of creating hole habitats versus pit habitats on intertidal artificial structures compare for biodiversity?",
  "relevant_summary": "Five studies on hole habitats (>50 mm) reported altered combined macroalgae and invertebrate community composition and/or the presence of species absent from unmodified surfaces when holes were added, often alongside other features (e.g., grooves, ridges, rock pools, or environmentally-sensitive material) [3467]. Three studies found increased combined macroalgae and invertebrate richness and/or diversity with holes, sometimes with other features [3467]. One study reported no increase in macroalgal abundance with holes, and two studies reported no increase or mixed effects on invertebrate abundance, including limpets depending on shore level and site; holes were used by sea slugs, urchins, and octopuses [3467].\n\nAcross 22 studies on pit habitats (1\u201350 mm), multiple replicated and randomized studies found pits altered community composition, with some reporting no change or mixed effects depending on pit size/arrangement, other added features, site, or shore level; several studies also noted pits supported species (macroalgae, invertebrates, and/or fish) absent from unmodified surfaces [3475]. Eight of 12 studies reported increased combined macroalgae and invertebrate richness and/or diversity with pits (often with grooves/ridges), while others found no increase or mixed effects; varying pit size/arrangement sometimes raised richness or had mixed/no effects [3475]. For abundance, studies reported increases, decreases, no effects, or mixed effects for combined macroalgae and invertebrates; macroalgal abundance often did not increase, while barnacle or mobile invertebrate abundances sometimes increased or varied with pit characteristics; fish richness and abundance increased in one study, and pits were used by limpets, periwinkles, macroalgae, invertebrates, and influenced fish feeding [3475].",
  "action_ids": [
