{
  "query": "In locations like Israel, the UK and Australia, how do outcomes vary when using environmentally-sensitive materials on subtidal artificial structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across Israel, the UK and Australia, studies reported that using environmentally-sensitive materials (e.g., shell-concrete, quarried rock, ECOncrete) often altered overall macroalgae and invertebrate community composition on artificial structure surfaces, although some studies found no change or mixed effects depending on material type and site (3470). Reported effects on species richness/diversity were mixed, with some cases (often involving ECOncrete with added texture, grooves, holes, pits or ledges) showing increases, while others using quarried rock or alternative cement mixes did not increase richness/diversity (3470). In the UK, one study found recycled-cement concrete did not increase diatom species richness (3470). For overall abundance, several studies in these regions found no increase or mixed responses; in one case ECOncrete increased live cover and biomass, while different concrete mixes supported differing cover and inorganic biomass (3470). For algae, studies in Australia, Israel and the UK reported no increases for several algal groups (e.g., brown, turf, coralline, diatoms) when using quarried rock or recycled-cement concrete, with some mixed outcomes and occasional increases for certain groups depending on site and material (3470). For invertebrates, studies in these regions reported mixed responses, including no increases for several sessile groups with quarried rock in some cases, a decrease for Spirorbid tubeworms in one case, and increased bivalve abundance with shell-concrete; different ECOncrete and standard-concrete mixes supported different coral abundances (3470). In Israel specifically, one study reported mixed effects on fish abundances when using ECOncrete with added grooves, holes and pits, varying by species group (3470).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3470"
  ]
}

