  "query": "What is the state of evidence for managing human activities, like maintenance and harvesting, on intertidal artificial structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "For managing or restricting harvesting on intertidal artificial structures, two studies were identified (Italy; Gibraltar and southeast Spain). No community-level responses were reported. A replicated, site-comparison study reported that restricting human access did not increase limpet abundance on structures, but did result in larger limpets with more balanced sex ratios than on unrestricted structures. A replicated, randomized study reported that legal access restrictions did not prevent people from harvesting invertebrates and fishes on and around structures [3458]. For ceasing or altering maintenance activities on intertidal artificial structures, no studies directly evaluated this intervention; therefore, there is no evidence indicating desirable or harmful effects [3440].",
