{
  "query": "To improve biodiversity on intertidal artificial structures, how do the outcomes of creating natural rocky reef topography compare to creating 'rock pools'?",
  "relevant_summary": "Creating natural rocky reef topography on intertidal artificial structures has limited evidence: one replicated, randomized, controlled study found no increase in combined macroalgae and invertebrate species richness on structure surfaces, and invertebrate (barnacle and mobile invertebrate) abundances showed mixed, site-dependent effects; created topography was colonized by macroalgae and limpets, and limpets used shaded grooves and water-retaining depressions [3435]. In contrast, creating rock pools is supported by more evidence across multiple regions: many replicated, controlled studies reported that pools supported macroalgae, invertebrate and/or fish species absent from flat surfaces, often with higher combined species richness and/or diversity than surfaces without pools, though several studies found similar richness and some outcomes depended on pool characteristics and site; abundance responses for macroalgae, invertebrates and fish were mixed; created pools were used by taxa including sea slugs, urchins, octopuses, macroalgae, invertebrates and fishes; fish species richness did not consistently increase [3476].",
