{
  "query": "How do the biodiversity outcomes of creating large hole habitats (>50mm) on artificial structures vary between subtidal zones in Israel and Sweden versus intertidal zones in Australia and Europe?",
  "relevant_summary": "Subtidal (Israel and Sweden): Across three replicated, controlled studies, adding >50 mm hole habitats (often alongside grooves, pits, small ledges or environmentally-sensitive materials) altered overall community composition on and around structures and supported mobile and/or non-mobile invertebrate and fish species absent from unmodified surfaces [3434]. Two of three studies reported increased combined macroalgae\u2013invertebrate richness and/or diversity, while one found no increase in combined mobile invertebrate and fish richness/diversity [3434]. Reported population-level effects included: no increase in combined mobile invertebrate and fish abundance off Sweden; mixed macroalgal and invertebrate abundance responses in Israel (including increases for brown crabs but not other mobile invertebrates); and mixed fish abundance responses when holes were added with other features [3434]. Intertidal (Australia and Europe): Replicated, controlled studies in Australia and the UK reported that hole habitats (often with rock pools or other microhabitats) supported macroalgae and/or non-mobile invertebrate species absent from unmodified surfaces, and increased combined macroalgae\u2013invertebrate richness and/or diversity on structure surfaces [3467]. In Europe, a replicated, paired study in the Netherlands reported no increase in macroalgal abundance, and studies in Australia and the Netherlands found no overall increase in invertebrate abundance or mixed limpet responses depending on shore level and site [3467]. One Australian study documented use of intertidal hole habitats by sea slugs, urchins and octopuses [3467].",
