  "query": "What are the general ecological effects of simultaneously creating grooves and small protrusions, ridges, or ledges on artificial structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across intertidal settings, 16 studies reported that adding grooves together with small protrusions/ridges/ledges (1\u201350 mm) often altered macroalgae\u2013invertebrate community composition, sometimes supporting species absent from untreated surfaces, though effects varied with site and design; species richness/diversity frequently increased but also showed mixed outcomes depending on groove/ridge size, arrangement, shore level, and other features; macroalgal and invertebrate richness showed mixed responses; fish species richness generally did not increase or showed site\u2011dependent responses; total macroalgae\u2013invertebrate abundance showed mixed results, with increases in some cases and no change in others; algal abundance responses were mixed or unchanged; invertebrate abundances (e.g., limpets, mussels, juvenile oysters, barnacles) were mixed, with oysters increasing in some cases while mobile invertebrates did not; fish abundance typically did not increase; grooves/protrusions were colonized by microalgae; and fish behavior sometimes changed (more time near surfaces, altered feeding) [3474]. In subtidal settings, three studies found that grooves with small protrusions/ledges could alter community composition and add species absent from plain surfaces, and richness/diversity increased in one study but showed mixed/no increases in another; overall macroalgae\u2013invertebrate abundance showed mixed responses depending on surface orientation; and added features were colonized by macroalgae and sessile invertebrates [3452].",
