{
  "query": "How do the biodiversity outcomes of creating small pits (1-50 mm) versus larger holes (>50 mm) on intertidal artificial structures compare?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across 22 studies, creating pit habitats (1\u201350 mm) on intertidal artificial structures: altered macroalgae and invertebrate community composition in several replicated, controlled studies, and supported species absent from unmodified surfaces in multiple studies [3475]; increased combined macroalgae and invertebrate richness and/or diversity in most of 12 replicated, controlled studies, with some studies showing no or mixed effects, and responses sometimes varying with pit size/arrangement and shore level [3475]; did not consistently increase macroalgal abundance in most of four replicated, controlled studies, with some mixed effects by pit size/arrangement and site [3475]; showed mixed effects on invertebrate abundances, with some studies reporting increases (including barnacles and mobile invertebrates), others no change or decreases, and some effects varying by species, site, animal size, pit size/arrangement, and density [3475]; increased fish community richness and abundance when pits were implemented with grooves in a replicated, randomized, controlled study, and altered fish community composition and behavior (more bites) in the same context [3475]; were used by periwinkles, limpets, macroalgae and other invertebrates, with occupancy varying by pit size/arrangement, species, animal size, site, and shore level [3475].\n\nAcross five studies, creating hole habitats (>50 mm) on intertidal artificial structures: altered macroalgae and invertebrate community composition in a replicated, randomized, paired, controlled, before-and-after study when combined with grooves, small ridges and environmentally sensitive material, and supported species absent from unmodified surfaces across studies (including when combined with rock pools or other features) [3467]; increased combined macroalgae and invertebrate richness and/or diversity in three replicated, controlled studies (often in combination with other features) [3467]; did not increase macroalgal abundance in one replicated, paired, controlled study [3467]; did not increase invertebrate abundance in one of two replicated, controlled studies, and had mixed effects on limpet abundance when combined with rock pools, varying by shore level and site [3467]; were used by sea slugs, urchins and octopuses in one study [3467].",
