{
  "query": "How do the biodiversity outcomes of creating small versus large protrusions, ridges or ledges on intertidal artificial structures compare?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across studies, small features and large features had different reported outcomes. Small protrusions (1\u201350 mm) increased combined macroalgae and invertebrate species richness in two studies, while effects on community composition and overall abundance were mixed and sometimes absent (3462). Small ridges or ledges (1\u201350 mm) often did not increase species richness or overall abundance; when present alongside other microhabitats outcomes were mixed, and ridges/ledges tended to support lower species richness and lower mobile invertebrate and oyster abundances than adjacent grooves, with fish richness and abundance similar to grooves (3464). Large protrusions (>50 mm) did not increase species richness in two studies, though they supported some invertebrate species absent from flat controls and increased limpet (but not barnacle) abundance; tilting protrusions changed community composition without increasing richness (3463). Large ridges or ledges (>50 mm) increased species diversity and overall abundance in some studies when installed with grooves and small protrusions, increased rockweed and mussel/limpet abundances (but not barnacles), but did not increase species richness in one study that combined large ridges with large protrusions; juvenile salmon abundance did not increase although feeding activity increased (3465). Overall, compared with small features, large ridges/ledges more often reported increases in diversity or abundance, whereas large protrusions did not increase richness, and small protrusions more consistently increased richness than small ridges/ledges (3462, 3463, 3464, 3465).",
