{
  "query": "In Australian estuaries, what factors influence the effectiveness of transplanting oysters onto intertidal artificial structures for enhancing wider biodiversity?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across replicated, randomized, controlled studies in Australian estuaries, transplanted oysters on intertidal artificial structures supported macroalgae, mobile and non-mobile invertebrates, and fish that were absent from unenhanced surfaces (3472). Effects on combined macroalgae\u2013invertebrate richness/diversity were mixed and depended on site and on the presence and size of surface microhabitats such as grooves, small ridges, or ledges (3472). Mobile invertebrate species richness increased on surfaces with transplanted oysters (3472). Overall macroalgae\u2013invertebrate abundance showed mixed or no increases, influenced by whether grooves, ridges, or ledges were present and their dimensions (3472). Mobile invertebrate abundance responses were mixed; in one study oyster recruit abundance increased and barnacle abundance decreased (3472). Fish species richness and abundance often did not increase, with responses varying by site and surface complexity; fish interaction time did not increase, though benthic fishes took more bites from oyster-only surfaces than from surfaces with oysters plus coralline algae (3472). Oyster survival was higher in grooves than on ridges, and survival in grooves versus on ledges varied by site; fish abundance around oysters was similar regardless of groove/ridge size (3472).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3472"
  ]
}

