{
  "query": "What are the effects of creating flexible habitats on the biodiversity of intertidal artificial structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from two actions indicates that creating flexible habitats on intertidal artificial structures can alter community composition, with variable effects on richness and abundance. Short flexible habitats (1\u201350 mm) on structures in Australia altered the combined macroalgae and non\u2011mobile invertebrate community composition on surfaces, had mixed effects on mobile invertebrate and fish community composition at low tide depending on site, did not alter mobile invertebrate or fish community composition at high tide, decreased combined macroalgae, invertebrate and fish species richness at low tide, had mixed effects on mobile invertebrate species richness at high tide depending on site, did not increase fish species richness at high tide, did not increase combined mobile invertebrate and fish abundance at low tide, had mixed effects on macroalgal abundance and on non\u2011mobile and mobile invertebrate abundances depending on species group and site, did not increase fish abundance at high tide, and did not increase the number of bites fishes took of structure surfaces [3459]. Long flexible habitats (>50 mm) on structures in the Netherlands altered the combined macroalgae and non\u2011mobile invertebrate community composition on surfaces, and the flexible habitats themselves supported macroalgae, mobile and non\u2011mobile invertebrates that were absent from surfaces without flexible habitats [3460].",
