{
  "query": "How do the biodiversity outcomes of creating 'rock pools' on intertidal artificial structures vary by location?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence spans multiple settings: estuaries (Australia, UK, eastern USA), open coastlines (UK, Ireland, southeast Spain), straits (UK, Malaysia), and a marina (Australia) (3476). Across these locations, created rock pools supported macroalgae, invertebrate, and/or fish species that were absent from adjacent structure surfaces, though one Australian study reported mixed community outcomes depending on pool depth, shore level, and site (3476). In Ireland, community composition varied with shore level and wave exposure, and wave\u2011sheltered pools infilled with sediment within two years (3476). Richness outcomes also varied across sites: most replicated controlled studies reported higher species richness/diversity in created pools than on flat surfaces, while several found similar richness, and one reported lower mobile invertebrate and fish richness compared to natural pools; effects sometimes varied by site, shore level, pool angle, and whether pools were tilted or horizontal (3476). Abundances and fish metrics showed mixed responses that depended on species group and site, indicating location\u2011dependent outcomes across the studied regions (3476).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3476"
  ]
}

