{
  "query": "How do the biodiversity outcomes of creating short flexible habitats compare with long flexible habitats on subtidal artificial structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across subtidal artificial structures, short flexible habitats (1\u201350 mm) produced mixed effects: community composition of mobile and/or non\u2011mobile invertebrates varied with density/length and site, and one study found altered non\u2011mobile invertebrate composition (Action 3450). They did not increase mobile or non\u2011mobile invertebrate species richness, and effects on mobile and non\u2011mobile invertebrate abundance were mixed by survey week, species group, length, or site; seahorse abundance also varied by week (Action 3450). In contrast, long flexible habitats (>50 mm) supported macroalgae and non\u2011mobile invertebrate or fish species absent from controls, and altered non\u2011mobile invertebrate community composition (Action 3451). Long habitats yielded higher combined macroalgae and invertebrate biomass than controls, with deeper habitats supporting higher biomass; invertebrate abundance responses were mixed, including decreased mussel abundance on structure surfaces alongside higher biomass on the flexible habitats themselves (Action 3451). Fish species richness and fish/seahorse abundances showed mixed responses depending on species, prior presence, or survey week, and seahorses used the long habitats (Action 3451).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3450",
    "3451"
  ]
}

